+    \section*{Appendix Y: Delay-Loop Mode Selection in Constrained Many-Body Fluids (Bridge Example)}
+    \label{app:pseudogap_delay_bridge}
+    \addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Appendix Y: Delay-Loop Mode Selection in Constrained Many-Body Fluids (Bridge Example)}
+
+    \subsection*{Y.1 Scope and status}
+    \textbf{Status: Bridge example (application note).}
+    This appendix records a condensed-matter application of the canonical delay-induced mode-selection mechanism from Sec.~\ref{sec:delay_mode_selection}.
+    It is included to document cross-domain reuse of the delay-loop formalism in a constrained many-body fluid setting relevant to pseudogap phenomenology.
+    No new SST primitives, axioms, or universal couplings are introduced here.
+
+    \subsection*{Y.2 Minimal bridge formulation}
+    Consider a closed collective-circulation path of effective length \(L\) with collective transport speed \(v\) in a constrained two-dimensional many-body fluid.
+    The finite return time
+    \begin{equation}
+        \tau = \frac{L}{v}
+    \end{equation}
+    induces delayed self-interaction of the phase variable around the loop.
+    In the long-delay regime, the same universality logic used in Sec.~\ref{sec:delay_mode_selection} applies:
+    delay selects admissible phase-locked circulation modes, while geometry/topology and dissipation determine which of those modes remain observable.
+
+    \subsection*{Y.3 Application-specific interpretation (non-canonical)}
+    In the pseudogap bridge interpretation, the delay-selected collective modes provide a hydrodynamic route to discrete collective energy scales and spectral-weight suppression without assuming that quasiparticles remain the fundamental carriers in the crossover regime.
+    This is an \emph{application-sector} claim only.
+    The effective quantities \((v,L,\tau)\) are phenomenological bridge parameters unless explicitly derived from a separate condensed-matter closure model.
+
+    \subsection*{Y.4 Kinematic scale estimate and caution}
+    A useful application estimate is the delay scale
+    \begin{equation}
+        \Delta E_{\tau} \sim \frac{h}{\tau},
+    \end{equation}
+    which may be used to organize candidate collective features in spectroscopy.
+    This estimate is a dimensional bridge heuristic and is not, by itself, a canonical SST prediction for pseudogap materials.
+
+    \subsection*{Y.5 Canonical role of this appendix}
+    The purpose of this appendix is strictly organizational:
+    it identifies a domain in which the canonical delay-loop mechanism may be reused, while preserving the Canon distinction between
+    (i) universal SST structure and
+    (ii) sector-specific effective modeling.
